.Im MicroEmacs command|spell|osd
.so me.tni
.TH describe-word 3
.XI describe-word - "Display a dictionary definition of a word"
.SH NAME
describe-word \- Display a dictionary definition of a word
.Me $a
.SH SYNOPSIS
.na
.B describe-word
"\fIword\fR"
.ad
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B describe-word
can be used to interface to an external dictionary to get a definition of a given word. When executed
\fBdescribe-word\fR will use the current word under the cursor as the initial \fIword\fR or will prompt the user if
the cursor is not in a word.
.PP
The command provides four methods of interfacing with an external dictionary and each language can be configured to
use one or more dictionaries, allowing secondary sources to be used if the primary lookup failed. The first interface
simply launches an external program which provides the definition in its own user interface, e.g. GoldenDict or MS
Bookshelf. A lookup using this interface is always assumed to be successful so this should always be the last one for 
a language.
.PP
The second interface launches an external program which prints out the definition to \fCstdout\fR, \*(mS can then pull
out the definition and display it in a \fB*describe-word*\fR buffer.
.PP
The third interface requires a URL, such as http:// or dict://, which provides the definition when loaded, and a 
clean-up macro the turns the definition into a readable form.
.PP
The last interface requires a dictionary text file, a regex search string and a clean-up macro.  \fBdescribe-word\fR 
loads the dictionary file and searches for definitions of the given word, adding each one to the output buffer, it 
then calls the clean-up macro to format the definitions into a more readable form. 
.SH NOTES
\fBdescribe-word\fR is a macro implemented in \fCword.emf\fR.
.PP
Due to the size and availability of dictionaries etc. \*(mS is released with describe-word set up to use the most
appropriate dictionaries available at \fCdict://dict.org/\fR.
.PP
\fBdescribe-word\fR must be setup for each required language, which requires the setting of a 
\fB.describe-word.<lang-id>\fR variable. The variable must be a
.Hl "\*(mS list" &lset 4
of dictionary interface configurations, each one being a sub-list to configure the interface to a dictionary source, 
each sub-list must take one of four forms:
.IP \fBExternal\fR
To interface with an external program the sub-list has the following items:
.RS
.CS
|<flags>|<source-name>|<not-used>|<command-line>|
.CE
Where:
.IP \fB<flags>\fR
Is a list of option flags, one of which must be \fCx\fR to indicate an external source. Other flags supported by an 
external source are \fCi\fR to use an ipipe to launch, this is useful when needing to debug the interface,
and \fCs\fR for a single, or shared, output buffer which is only used when ipipe mode is also being used.
.IP \fB<source-name>\fR
Defines the name of the interface, or source, and is only used when ipipe mode is also being used.
.IP \fB<not-used>\fR
The 3rd item is not currently used and should be left empty.
.IP \fB<command-line>\fR
Defines the command-line required to launch the external dictionary program, the \fB<command-line>\fR should contain a
\fC%w\fR token which is replaced with the given word, the token will typically also require surrounding \fC%"\fR
tokens (i.e. \fC%"%w%"\fR) so that if the word contains a space it will be properly quoted in the generated
command-line.
.RE
.IP \fBCommand\fR
To interface with an external program which prints the definition out to \fCstdout\fR, the sub-list has the following items:
.RS
.CS
|<flags>|<source-name>|<clean-up-macro>|<command-line>|
.CE
Where:
.IP \fB<flags>\fR
Is a list of option flags, one of which must be \fCc\fR to indicate a command source. The only other flags currently 
supported by a command source is \fCs\fR for a single, or shared, output buffer, without this flag the buffer name 
includes the word being described.
.IP \fB<source-name>\fR
Defines the name of the interface, or source, which is used in the details given in the first line of the output buffer.
.IP \fB<clean-up-macro>\fR
The clean-up macro has two purposes, firstly if the macro aborts (i.e. calls
.Ht !abort 4
etc.) it signals to \fBdescribe-word\fR that the output does not actually contain a definition, for example the output 
may simply be "\fCNo definitions found for <word>\fR". The second purpose is to perform any clean-up and reformatting 
required to make the output more legible. \fBdescribe-word\fR provides a simple \fBdescribe-word-cmd\fR macro which 
simply aborts if the output contains one line with the line starting with "\fCNo definitions found for \fR".
.IP \fB<command-line>\fR
Defines the command-line required to launch the dictionary program, the \fB<command-line>\fR should contain a \fC%w\fR 
token which is replaced with the given word, the token will typically also require surrounding \fC%"\fR tokens (i.e. 
\fC%"%w%"\fR) so that if the word contains a space it will be properly quoted in the generated command-line.
.RE
.IP \fBURL\fR
To interface with an online dictionary source, the sub-list has the following items:
.RS
.CS
|<flags>|<source-name>|<clean-up-macro>|<url>|
.CE
Where:
.IP \fB<flags>\fR
Is a list of option flags, one of which must be \fCu\fR to indicate a URL source. The only other flags currently 
supported by a URL source is \fCs\fR for a single, or shared, output buffer, without this flag the buffer name 
includes the word being described.
.IP \fB<source-name>\fR
Defines the name of the interface, or source, which is used in the details given in the first line of the output buffer.
.IP \fB<clean-up-macro>\fR
The clean-up macro has two purposes, firstly if the macro aborts (i.e. calls
.Ht !abort 4
etc.) it signals to \fBdescribe-word\fR that the output does not actually contain a definition, for example the output 
may simply be a network error. The second purpose is to perform any clean-up and reformatting 
required to make the output more legible. \fBdescribe-word\fR provides a \fBdescribe-word-dct\fR macro for 
\fCdict://\fR URLs which aborts if the output contains less than three lines. It also reformats the output to improve 
the output in \*(mS.
.IP \fB<url>\fR
Defines the URL required to get a definition, the \fB<url>\fR should contain either a \fC%w\fR 
token, which is replaced with the given word in plain text, or \fC%e\fR which is replaced with the given word 
URL-encoded (also known as percent encoded).
.RE
.IP \fBFile\fR
To interface with a dictionary text file, the sub-list has the following items:
.RS
.CS
|<flags>|<source-name>|<clean-up-macro>|<regex-search>|<dict-file>|
.CE
Where:
.IP \fB<flags>\fR
Is a list of option flags, one of which must be \fCf\fR to indicate a file source. Other flags currently supported by
a file source are \fCk\fR to keep the dictionary file loaded (improves performance at a cost of increased memory
usage), \fCm\fR to indication that the dictionary may contain multiple definitions of the same word, and \fCs\fR for a
single, or shared, output buffer, without this flag the buffer name includes the word being described.
.IP \fB<source-name>\fR
Defines the name of the interface, or source, which is used in the details given in the first line of the output buffer.
.IP \fB<clean-up-macro>\fR
The clean-up macro has two purposes, firstly if the macro aborts (i.e. calls
.Ht !abort 4
etc.) it signals to \fBdescribe-word\fR that the output does not actually contain a definition. The second purpose is to perform any clean-up and reformatting 
required to make the output more legible. \fBdescribe-word\fR provides a \fBdescribe-word-sln\fR macro which 
attempts to convert a single line of definition text into a better laid out set of definitions.
.IP \fB<regex-search>\fR
Defines the regex search string required to find the definition of a given word, it must contain a \fC%r\fR 
token which is replaced with the given word (but regex encoded, i.e. '.' to '\\.' etc) and at least on group, the 
first of which must fully contain the definition.
.IP \fB<dict-file>\fR
The file name of the dictionary, this can be an absolute file name or given without the path if the file is located in 
a directory in the \*(mS
.Ht $search-path 5 .
.RE
Each interface sub-list must be wrapped up in the main setup list, which must use a different list separator 
character.
.PP
Note that if spelling has also been setup for the current language, when \fBdescribe-word\fR fails to find a 
definition it will use the
.Ht spell 2
interface to extract the base word (i.e. base of \fCwords\fR is \fCword\fR) and search for a definition of the base 
word. When a language is configured to use multiple interfaces, the actual word and then the base is looked-up in the 
primary interface before moving to the secondary etc.
.SH EXAMPLE
The following example configures \fBdescribe-word\fR to use the online \fBdict://dict.org/\fR \fBWordNet\fR English 
dictionary:
.Me $emf-scheme
.CS
set-variable .describe-word.enus "!|u|WordNet|describe-word-dct|dict://dict.org/d:%w:wn|!"
.CE
.Me $ehf-scheme
WordNet is a good modern English dictionary, but it has less than 150K word definitions. To improve the likelihood of 
finding a definition, a secondary source can be added:
.Me $emf-scheme
.CS
set-variable .describe-word.enus "!|u|WordNet|describe-word-dct|dict://dict.org/d:%w:wn|!|u||describe-word-dct|dict://dict.org/d:%w:*|!"
.CE
.Me $ehf-scheme
The changed of \fCwm\fR to \fC*\fR at the end of the \fCdict://\fR URL requests the dictionary server to search all 
available dictionaries. Alternatively, if the
.Hr dict 1
utility is installed, it can be used instead, as follows:
.Me $emf-scheme
.CS
set-variable .describe-word.enus "!|c||describe-word-cmd|dict %\\"%w%\\"|!"
.CE
.Me $ehf-scheme
Note the enclosing of \fC%w\fR with \fC%"\fR tokens to ensure the correct encoding/formatting of the command-line.
.PP
Alternatively, if the
.Hr GoldenDict 1
utility is installed, the following can be used to simply launch the utility:
.Me $emf-scheme
.CS
set-variable .describe-word.enus "!|x|GoldenDict||goldendict %\\"%w%\\"|!"
.CE
.Me $ehf-scheme
Note however that \*(mS has no way to detect whether a definition was found, so it has to assume it was. As a result 
this interface should be last as no further interfaces will be used.
.PP
If available, the use of a local dictionary text file can greatly improve performance, the dictionary file typically 
contains the word at the start of a line, followed by a delimiter, such as a tab character, and then the definition in 
the rest of the line. \fBdescribe-word\fR can be configured to use such a file as follows:
.Me $emf-scheme
.CS
set-variable .describe-word.enus "!|fkms|My Dictionary File|describe-word-sln|^%r\\t\\\\(.*\\\\)|mydict.txt|!"
.CE
.Me $ehf-scheme
Where \fCmydict.txt\fR is the name of the dictionary file and is located in the \*(mS search path. This could be 
combined with other sources such as \fCdict.org\fR or \fBGoldenDict\fR, to create a comprehensive dictionary look-up:
.Me $emf-scheme
.CS
set-variable .describe-word.enus "!|fkms|My Dictionary File|describe-word-sln|^%r\\t\\\\(.*\\\\)|mydict.txt|!|u|WordNet|describe-word-dct|dict://dict.org/d:%w:wn|!|x|GoldenDict||goldendict %\\"%w%\\"|!"
.CE
.Me $ehf-scheme
The required variables should be added to the user setup file. Notes that, as some interfaces could use '\fC!\fR' or
\&'\fC|\fR' characters in their configuration, \*(mS uses different list separator characters, typically \fC\\f\fR
place of \fC!\fR and \fC\\b\fR instead of \fC|\fR. 
